    <article class="article-section" aria-labelledby="article-h2">
      <h2 id="article-h2">How to Calculate Loan EMI in India</h2>
      <p>EMI stands for <strong>Equated Monthly Instalment</strong> — the fixed amount you pay your lender every month to repay a loan. Each EMI consists of two parts: a portion that goes toward repaying the principal (original loan amount) and a portion that covers the interest charged by the bank.</p>

      <h3>EMI Formula</h3>
      <p>The standard formula used by all banks and financial institutions to calculate EMI is:</p>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <strong>EMI = P × r × (1 + r)^n / [(1 + r)^n – 1]</strong><br/><br/>
        Where:<br/>
        P = Principal loan amount<br/>
        r = Monthly interest rate (Annual rate ÷ 12 ÷ 100)<br/>
        n = Loan tenure in months
      </div>
      <p>For example, for a ₹25 lakh home loan at 8.5% for 20 years: r = 8.5/12/100 = 0.00708, n = 240. The EMI works out to approximately ₹21,699 per month.</p>

      <h3>Types of Loans and Typical Interest Rates (2025)</h3>
      <table aria-label="Typical loan interest rates in India 2025">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Loan Type</th><th>Typical Rate (2025)</th><th>Max Tenure</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Home Loan</td><td><span class="rate-chip">8.5% – 10.5%</span></td><td>30 years</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Car Loan</td><td><span class="rate-chip">8.7% – 12.5%</span></td><td>7 years</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Personal Loan</td><td><span class="rate-chip">10.5% – 18%</span></td><td>5 years</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Education Loan</td><td><span class="rate-chip">8.5% – 14%</span></td><td>15 years</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>How to Reduce Your EMI</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Larger down payment:</strong> Pay more upfront to reduce the principal and thus the EMI.</li>
        <li><strong>Longer tenure:</strong> Spreading repayment over more months reduces monthly EMI — but increases total interest paid.</li>
        <li><strong>Balance transfer:</strong> If you find a lower interest rate elsewhere, a loan balance transfer can significantly reduce EMI.</li>
        <li><strong>Part prepayment:</strong> Making lump-sum payments toward principal reduces your outstanding balance and EMI.</li>
        <li><strong>Negotiate rate:</strong> A good CIBIL score (750+) gives you leverage to negotiate a lower interest rate with your bank.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>What is an Amortization Schedule?</h3>
      <p>An amortization table shows the month-by-month breakdown of every EMI payment — exactly how much goes to principal and how much to interest. In early months, the interest component is high. As the loan matures, more of each EMI goes toward principal repayment. This is why prepaying a loan early in its tenure saves the most interest.</p>

      <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--muted);margin-top:8px;font-style:italic;">Disclaimer: EMI figures are calculated estimates. Actual EMIs may vary based on your lender's specific terms. Always verify with your bank before making financial decisions.</p>
    </article>

    <!-- ── FAQ ── -->
    <section class="faq-section" aria-labelledby="faq-h2">
      <h2 id="faq-h2">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">How is EMI calculated? <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></div>
        <div class="faq-a" role="region">EMI = P × r × (1+r)^n ÷ [(1+r)^n – 1], where P is principal, r is the monthly interest rate (annual rate ÷ 12 ÷ 100), and n is the number of months. Our calculator applies this formula automatically.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">What is a good EMI-to-income ratio? <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></div>
        <div class="faq-a" role="region">Most financial advisors recommend keeping total EMIs below 40% of your net monthly income. Banks typically cap loan eligibility at 50–60% FOIR (Fixed Obligation to Income Ratio). Keeping EMIs under 30% gives you financial breathing room.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">Does prepayment reduce EMI or tenure? <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></div>
        <div class="faq-a" role="region">Both options are available depending on your bank's policy. Reducing tenure while keeping the same EMI saves more in total interest. Reducing EMI while keeping tenure gives you immediate cash flow relief. Most banks allow you to choose.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">What is the EMI for a ₹50 lakh home loan for 20 years at 9%? <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></div>
        <div class="faq-a" role="region">For a ₹50 lakh home loan at 9% p.a. for 20 years (240 months), the EMI is approximately ₹44,986 per month. Total interest paid over the loan period would be around ₹57.97 lakh — more than the principal itself. Use our calculator above for exact figures.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">Is EMI tax deductible in India? <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></div>
        <div class="faq-a" role="region">For home loans, the interest component of EMI is deductible under Section 24(b) up to ₹2 lakh per year, and the principal component is deductible under Section 80C up to ₹1.5 lakh per year. Education loan interest is fully deductible under Section 80E for 8 years. Personal and car loan EMIs generally have no tax deduction.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q" role="button" tabindex="0" aria-expanded="false">What happens if I miss an EMI? <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></div>
        <div class="faq-a" role="region">Missing an EMI results in a late payment penalty (typically 1–2% of the overdue amount), a negative mark on your CIBIL credit report, and potential penal interest. Multiple missed EMIs can lead to the loan account being classified as NPA (Non-Performing Asset) and legal action by the lender.</div>
      </div>

    </section>

